  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Memorial on Prohibiting Extravagance and Ostentation
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The foundation of governing a realm lies in frugality and simplicity. How much more so for our nation, where the land is cramped and the people impoverished—we must cherish austerity above all else.

    Since we came under the Yuan's dominion, rich tributes have flowed between courts, and with them a tide of extravagance has swept in. The people's hearts have grown arrogant and proud, all stemming from this very cause. It is for this reason that Your Highness, in the year of Byungsin, issued a sacred decree: "Only officials of the second rank and above may use vessels and furnishings of gold and jade. Silken flowers, phoenix ornaments, and honeyed delicacies shall be reserved solely for offerings to the Buddha and the gods; all other uses are hereby forbidden."

    Yet of late, the winds of extravagance have risen again. Now even common folk presume to use such treasures, and the prices of goods have soared precipitously. This is no way to ensure the nation's enduring prosperity.

    I humbly beseech Your Majesty: let the earlier sacred decree be faithfully upheld, and let the spirit of simplicity and humility be renewed and strengthened. How greatly this would be desired.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Byungsin (丙申) refers to a year in the Korean calendar cycle; the decree mentioned is a historical royal edict against extravagance.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to serving under the Yuan reflects Korea's historical tributary relationship with Mongol-era China.
